source: Expense ratio is the percentage of the mutal fund share price shareholders are charged each year by the mutual fund company
The stock market has been performing well the last 5 years. The average mutual fund has increased 87%!

data.groupby('over1B')[['Basic Materials', 'Consumer Cyclical', 'Financial Services', 'Realestate',
       'Consumer Defensive', 'Healthcare', 'Utilities',
       'Communication Services', 'Energy', 'Industrials', 'Technology']].mean().plot(kind='bar')

plt.legend(['Basic Materials', 'Consumer Cyclical', 'Financial Services', 'Real Estate',
       'Consumer Defensive', 'Healthcare', 'Utilities',
       'Communication Services', 'Energy', 'Industrials', 'Technology'], bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.)

plt.xticks([True, False],['Over $1 Billion NAV', 'Under $1 Billion NAV'], rotation = 0)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Average Percentage')
plt.title('Fund Holdings by Industry')

Here we examined how the past performance of a mutual fund related to its future performance. We did see a that in general, funds that performed well in the past also performed well in the future. However, the correlation wasn't extremely strong, and many of the funds that performed extremely well in the past underperformed in the future. The correlation depended a little on where you ended the "before" percent change and began the "after" percent change.

def comparePriceChanges(cutoff):
    before = stock_prices.loc[cutoff]/stock_prices.loc['2012-06-01']
    after = stock_prices.loc['2017-06-01']/stock_prices.loc[cutoff]
    plt.scatter(before, after)
    plt.xlabel('Price Change Before ' + cutoff)
    plt.ylabel('Price Change After ' + cutoff)
    plt.title('Comparing Fund Price Changes Over the Past 5 Years')

It seems that the general trend still holds, except for a few funds that performed very well prior to june 2015 did poorly afterwards. You can see this in the wierd tail-like pattern that runs perpendicular to the general trend.

We investigated this trend of funds performing well before 2015-06-01 but doing poorly afterwards. We took the funds that had the 10 highest difference in performance before and after 2015-06-01, and we looked them up on yahoo finance. We found that they were all biotech funds. Biotech seems to be the only sector where past performance hasn't correlated positively with future performance.
